    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div rend="parallel">
                <p xml:id="KT388-kilavi">talaimakaḷ uṭaṉpōkku nērntamai uṇarnta talaimakaṉ curattu
                    vemmaiyun talaimakaḷ meṉmaiyuṅ kuṟittuc celavaḻuṅkaluṟuvāṉait tōḻi aḻuṅkāmaṟ
                    kūṟiyatu. </p>


                <p xml:lang="en">HE, who realised HER consent to going away
                    together, the confidante speaking of not avoiding to him, who thinks of avoiding
                    to go, considering the heat of the desert and HER tenderness. </p>
            </div>

            <div rend="parallel">
                <lg xml:id="KT388">
                    <l> nīrkāl yātta niraiyitaḻk kuvaḷai</l>
                    <l> kōṭai yoṟṟiṉum vāṭā tākuṅ</l>
                    <l> kavaṇai yaṉṉa pūṭṭupporu tacāa</l>
                    <l> vumaṇerut toḻukait tōṭunirait taṉṉa</l>
                    <l> muḷiciṉai piḷakku muṉpiṉ maiyiṉ</l>
                    <l> yāṉai kaimaṭit tuyavuṅ</l>
                    <l> kāṉamu miṉiyavā nummoṭu variṉē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg xml:lang="en">
                    <l> The waterlily with petals in a row, crowding in the water,</l>
                    <l> even if oppressed by the west wind, won’t fade,</l>
                    <l> [and], <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">ākum </term> (line 2) and <term xml:lang="ta">ām </term>
                        (line 7) are used in embedding function, the former for embedding an
                        aphorism, the latter for the main sentence statement. Have both to be
                        coordinated by "and"?</note> if [she] comes with you, even the forests
                        will be pleasing, <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">ām</term> can either be dynamic ("will become") or
                        predicative, that is, the ascertainment of a fact.</note>
                    </l>
                    <l rend="indent"> where elephants are suffering, trunks drooping,</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> for the destitution of former times,</l>
                    <l rend="indent7"> when they [still] split dry twigs,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> standing <note place="foot">What is put in row can either be
                        the exhausted animals, or, as T.V.G. asserts, the trees which with their
                        raised dried branches remind of the open wood carts. In both cases the image
                        is optical: they evoke the sight of a caravan.</note> in a row – like a mass
                        of salt-merchants' ox-carts,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> struck <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">porutu </term> is actually absolutive, that is, we
                        have an anacolouth, since with <term xml:lang="ta"> acāa</term> as the
                        subject of <term xml:lang="ta">porutu</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">pūṭṭu </term>
                        we would expect <term xml:lang="ta">acāa poruta</term> .</note> by languor
                        [and] fastened as if in a sling <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">kavaṇai aṉṉa pūṭṭu </term> is taken by T.V.G. as
                        referring only to the oxen and rendered as "yoked as if with a stone", of
                        which meaning for <term xml:lang="ta">kavaṇai </term> there is no trace in
                        the dictionaries.</note> . <note place="foot">Line 3 can either be connected with the ox-cart comparison
                        or directly with the elephants.</note>
                    </l>


                </lg>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
